Code Arena — Project Document & Requirements

**Code Arena**

Project Document & Requirements Specification

*A competitive coding contest platform for developers and students*

| **Version** | 1.0 (Draft) |
| --- | --- |
| **Date** | June 20, 2026 |
| **Status** | For review |
| **Product type** | Competitive coding contest platform (timed contests, leaderboards) |
| **Primary audience** | Individual developers and students |

**Table of Contents**

# 1. Overview & Vision

Code Arena is a web-based platform where developers and students compete in timed coding contests, solve algorithmic problems against the clock, and climb global and contest-specific leaderboards. The experience centers on the thrill of competition: a contest starts, the clock runs, submissions are judged in real time, and rankings shift live as participants solve problems.

The vision is to be the place where individual coders sharpen their skills through regular, well-run competition — combining the rigor of a serious online judge with a motivating progression system (ratings, ranks, streaks) that keeps people coming back. Unlike pure practice sites, the heartbeat of Code Arena is the live contest.

# 2. Goals & Objectives

The product aims to run reliable, low-latency timed contests where verdicts return in seconds; keep participants engaged through a transparent rating system and persistent leaderboards; lower the barrier for newcomers with a clear difficulty ladder and a practice mode; and build a self-sustaining content pipeline of quality problems. Early success looks like recurring contests with strong return participation and a judging system trusted to be fast and fair.

# 3. Target Users & Personas

The platform serves three closely related personas:

- Competitive Climber — an experienced developer chasing a higher rating and a strong leaderboard finish; cares about speed, fairness, and accurate ratings.

- Learning Student — a newer coder, often a CS student or bootcamp attendee, who wants structured practice and gentle on-ramps before competing seriously.

- Casual Returner — drops in for the occasional weekend contest and wants a frictionless join-and-go experience without heavy setup.

# 4. Scope

## 4.1 In Scope (v1)

User accounts and profiles; a problem bank with difficulty tiers; scheduled timed contests; a real-time code execution and judging engine; multi-language support; live and historical leaderboards; a rating system; submission history; and a practice/archive mode for past problems.

## 4.2 Out of Scope (v1)

Team/squad contests; real-time 1v1 head-to-head battles; in-platform interview or hiring tooling; payments and paid tiers; mobile native apps; and a community forum or discussion system. These are candidates for later phases.

# 5. Functional Requirements

## 5.1 Accounts & Profiles

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-1** | Users can register and authenticate via email/password and at least one OAuth provider (e.g., GitHub, Google). |
| **FR-2** | Each user has a public profile showing handle, current rating, rank tier, contest history, and solved-problem count. |
| **FR-3** | Users can set a preferred default programming language and editor preferences. |

## 5.2 Problem Bank

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-4** | Problems include a statement, constraints, input/output format, sample cases, and hidden judge test cases. |
| **FR-5** | Each problem is tagged with difficulty (Easy/Medium/Hard or a numeric rating) and topic tags (arrays, graphs, DP, etc.). |
| **FR-6** | Problems support per-problem time and memory limits enforced by the judge. |
| **FR-7** | The system stores multiple solutions/test sets per problem and supports problem versioning for setters. |

## 5.3 Contests

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-8** | Admins/problem setters can schedule contests with a start time, fixed duration, and a defined problem set. |
| **FR-9** | Users can register for upcoming contests; the contest page shows a countdown and, once live, a running timer. |
| **FR-10** | During a live contest, problems unlock at start and submissions are accepted only within the contest window. |
| **FR-11** | The system supports common scoring models — at minimum ICPC-style (problems solved + penalty time) and points-based scoring; configurable per contest. |
| **FR-12** | Contests support a configurable post-start “freeze” period during which the public leaderboard stops updating to preserve final-standings suspense. |

## 5.4 Code Execution & Judging

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-13** | Users write and submit code in an in-browser editor with syntax highlighting for all supported languages. |
| **FR-14** | Submissions are compiled and executed in a sandboxed, resource-limited environment isolated from other users and the host. |
| **FR-15** | The judge returns standard verdicts: Accepted, Wrong Answer, Time Limit Exceeded, Memory Limit Exceeded, Runtime Error, Compilation Error — with a failing-test indicator where appropriate. |
| **FR-16** | Verdicts for typical submissions return within a few seconds under normal contest load. |
| **FR-17** | Users can run their code against sample cases before submitting (a non-scored test run). |
| **FR-18** | The system maintains a full submission history per user with timestamps, verdict, language, and runtime/memory used. |

## 5.5 Leaderboards & Ratings

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-19** | Each contest has a live leaderboard ranking participants per the contest’s scoring model, updating in near real time (subject to freeze rules). |
| **FR-20** | A global all-time leaderboard ranks users by rating. |
| **FR-21** | After a rated contest concludes, the system recomputes participant ratings using an Elo/Glicko-style algorithm and updates rank tiers. |
| **FR-22** | Users can view historical leaderboards and their own contest-by-contest rating changes. |

## 5.6 Practice / Archive

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-23** | After a contest, its problems move to a searchable archive available for untimed practice. |
| **FR-24** | Users can filter the archive by difficulty, topic tag, and solved/unsolved status. |
| **FR-25** | Practice submissions are judged identically to contest submissions but do not affect rating. |

## 5.7 Notifications

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **FR-26** | Users receive reminders for contests they’ve registered for (in-app and/or email). |

# 6. Non-Functional Requirements

| **ID** | **Requirement** |
| --- | --- |
| **NFR-1** | Performance — Judging latency stays within a few seconds at the 95th percentile during peak contest load; pages load quickly even with large leaderboards. |
| **NFR-2** | Scalability — The judging layer scales horizontally to absorb the submission spike at contest start, when many participants submit within a short window. |
| **NFR-3** | Security & Isolation — Submitted code runs in a strict sandbox with no network access, capped CPU/memory/time, and no access to the host or other submissions. |
| **NFR-4** | Fairness & Integrity — Server clocks are authoritative for contest timing; basic plagiarism/duplicate-detection signals are captured for review. |
| **NFR-5** | Availability — Target high availability during scheduled contest windows, with graceful handling of judge backpressure (queue + status feedback rather than dropped submissions). |
| **NFR-6** | Consistency — Leaderboard and rating computations are deterministic and reproducible from the submission log. |
| **NFR-7** | Accessibility & Compatibility — Works on current major desktop browsers; the editor and contest UI meet baseline accessibility standards. |
| **NFR-8** | Observability — Submission throughput, judge queue depth, and verdict latency are monitored with alerting during contests. |

# 7. Representative User Stories

- As a competitor, I register for the Saturday contest, get a reminder, join at start, and watch my rank move as I solve problems — so I feel the live competition.

- As a student, I filter the archive for Easy graph problems and practice untimed with full judge feedback — so I can build up before competing.

- As any user, I submit code and get a clear verdict within seconds, including which sample failed — so I can iterate quickly under time pressure.

- As a competitor, I review my rating change after a contest and see the math behind it — so I trust the ranking system.

# 8. High-Level Technical Architecture

A typical shape for this system includes a web frontend (SPA) for the contest UI and editor; an application/API service handling accounts, contests, problems, and leaderboards; a dedicated judge service consisting of a submission queue and a pool of isolated execution workers (containerized sandboxes with enforced resource limits); a primary relational database for users, problems, contests, and submissions; a fast cache/store for live leaderboard state; and object storage for problem test data. The submission queue decouples the spike of contest-start submissions from the worker pool so the system degrades gracefully under load rather than failing.

# 9. Success Metrics

Track contest participation (registered vs. actually competing), return rate across consecutive contests, judge verdict latency (p50/p95), problem-solve rates by difficulty, new-user activation (first contest entered, first problem solved), and rating distribution health. The single most important reliability metric is verdict latency under peak load — it underpins trust in the whole platform.

# 10. Suggested Phasing

- Phase 1 (MVP) — Accounts, the problem bank, the judging engine with core languages, a single scheduled contest type with a live leaderboard, and the archive.

- Phase 2 — The rating/rank-tier system, the leaderboard freeze, notifications, and richer profiles.

- Phase 3 — Deferred items: team contests, real-time 1v1 battles, and community features, based on traction.

# 11. Risks & Mitigations

The central risk is the judging engine: sandbox escapes (mitigated with hardened, network-isolated containers and strict resource caps) and the contest-start submission spike (mitigated with a queue and horizontally scalable workers). Rating fairness is a trust risk — mitigated by choosing a well-understood algorithm and making changes transparent. Content supply is a sustainability risk — a thin problem bank kills competitive value, so a setter pipeline and quality bar matter early. Cheating and plagiarism threaten leaderboard integrity and need at least basic detection from the start.

# 12. Open Questions

- Which programming languages to support at launch?

- Are v1 contests rated from day one, or do they start unrated?

- Which rating algorithm — Elo, Glicko, or a Codeforces-style variant?

- How are problems sourced and vetted — in-house setters, invited contributors, or both?

